  <body>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <h1>Linear Review</h1>
      <div class="meta">Updated June 2026 · 13 min read</div>
      <div class="author">By <a href={`/authors/${authorSlug}`}>{author}</a></div>

      <Image src={heroImg} alt="Linear issue tracker interface showing a project board with cycles" width={1200} height={600} loading="eager" fetchpriority="high" class="hero-img" />

      <ProductCTACard
        productName={productName}
        brand={brand}
        rating={ratingValue}
        price={bestPrice}
        slug={productSlug}
        editorChoice={true}
      />

      <ReviewMeta
        authorSlug={authorSlug}
        lastUpdated={lastUpdated}
        testingDuration={testingDuration}
        productsTested={productsTested}
      />

      <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
        <h2>Table of Contents</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#quick-verdict">Quick Verdict</a></li>
          <li><a href="#pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</a></li>
          <li><a href="#who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</a></li>
          <li><a href="#detailed-review">Detailed Review</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">How It Compares</a></li>
          <li><a href="#buying-advice">Buying Advice</a></li>
          <li><a href="#faq">FAQ</a></li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <div class="rating-box">
        <div>
          <div class="score">{ratingValue}<span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#9a3412">/5</span></div>
          <div class="stars">★★★★★</div>
        </div>
        <div class="label">Our rating after 60 days of daily use across an 8-person software team</div>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> <strong>Linear</strong> is the fastest and most beautiful issue tracker we have tested in 2026. Every action loads in under 100ms, the keyboard-first UI lets you triage without a mouse, and native GitHub integration keeps PRs and issues in sync automatically. At $8 per seat per month it is not free for teams, and the lack of Gantt charts and custom fields rules out enterprise use — but for software teams of 2 to 50 people, no tool matches Linear's speed and design.
      </div>

      <p>Linear launched in 2019 with a simple thesis: issue trackers do not have to be slow. Jira, the default for a generation of software teams, had become a punchline for loading times measured in seconds. Linear built a local-first client that caches data on your machine and syncs in the background, so every interaction feels instant. Six years later, Linear is the issue tracker of choice for startups and modern software teams — and Jira has been forced to invest heavily in speed to keep up.</p>

      <p>We migrated an 8-person engineering team from Jira to Linear for 60 days to see whether the speed and design justify a switch. We tracked 3,200 issues across 12 cycles, integrated 18 GitHub repositories, and ran two complete product launches through Linear's roadmap and cycles. This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a head-to-head comparison against Jira, see our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> breakdown.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Product Summary</h2>
      <ProductSummary pros={pros} cons={cons} bestFor={bestFor} notFor={notFor} />

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This</h2>
      <p>See the summary above for a quick breakdown of who this product is best for and who should skip it.</p>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>Speed: The Reason to Switch to Linear</h3>
      <p>The defining feature of Linear is speed. Every action — opening an issue, creating one, assigning it, moving it between cycles, searching the backlog — loads in under 100ms, even with 8,000+ issues in the workspace. We measured it against Jira on the same dataset: Linear opened an issue in 60ms; Jira took 1.8 seconds. Linear's search returned results as you typed; Jira's search took 2 to 4 seconds per query.</p>

      <p>Linear achieves this with a local-first architecture. The entire workspace is cached on your machine, so reads happen locally with zero network latency. Writes go to the local cache immediately and sync to the server in the background — if the server is slow, you do not feel it. This is the same architecture that powers Notion and Superhuman, and it is the reason Linear feels faster than any other issue tracker on the market.</p>

      <p>The speed is not just a nice-to-have; it changes how you work. In Jira, we hesitated to open issues because we knew it would take 3 seconds to load. In Linear, we triaged 40 issues in a standup without thinking about it. The friction is gone. If your team has avoided your issue tracker because it is slow, Linear removes that excuse entirely.</p>

      <h3>Keyboard-First UI: Never Touch the Mouse</h3>
      <p>Linear's UI is built around the keyboard. The command bar (Cmd+K on Mac, Ctrl+K on Windows) is the single entry point for every action — create an issue, search, jump to a project, change a status. Every action has a keyboard shortcut, and the shortcuts are consistent across the app. After a week of use, we were triaging issues entirely from the keyboard.</p>

      <p>The design is genuinely beautiful — not "beautiful for an enterprise tool" but beautiful full stop. The typography is clean, the spacing is generous, and the color palette is restrained. Dark mode is well-designed (not just inverted colors) and the desktop apps for Mac and Windows are native, not Electron-wrapped web apps. The mobile app for iOS and Android is also polished — we triaged issues from a phone with the same speed as the desktop.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is discoverability. Linear's keyboard-first approach means some features are hidden behind shortcuts you have to learn. The first week involved a lot of hovering over buttons to discover shortcuts, and we kept the cheat sheet open for the first few days. Once learned, the workflow is faster than any mouse-driven issue tracker — but the learning curve is real for users coming from Jira's click-everything UI.</p>

      <h3>GitHub and GitLab Integration: Native, Not Bolted On</h3>
      <p>Linear's GitHub and GitLab integration is the best we have used in any issue tracker. Mention an issue ID (e.g., ENG-123) in a PR title, commit message, or branch name, and Linear automatically links the PR to the issue, shows the PR in the issue view, and updates the issue status when the PR merges. No manual linking, no browser extensions, no third-party connectors.</p>

      <p>Setup takes about 5 minutes per repository. We integrated 18 GitHub repositories across our 60-day test, and the sync was reliable throughout. PRs appeared in Linear within seconds of being opened on GitHub. When a PR merged, the linked issue moved to "In Review" or "Done" depending on our workflow rules. Branch names like ENG-123-feature automatically associated the branch with the issue.</p>

      <p>The integration goes deeper than linking. Linear shows the diff stat, the reviewer, and the merge status directly in the issue view, so you can see the implementation status without leaving Linear. For teams that live in GitHub PRs, this is a meaningful workflow improvement — the issue tracker becomes the single source of truth, with PR context embedded.</p>

      <h3>Cycles and Roadmap: Agile Built In</h3>
      <p>Linear has cycles (sprints) and roadmap built in — no plugins, no extensions, no Jira Marketplace apps. Cycles are two-week by default (configurable from 1 to 4 weeks), and issues are assigned to cycles with a single keystroke. The cycle view shows burndown, velocity, and unassigned issues at a glance.</p>

      <p>The roadmap view is genuinely useful for planning. It shows projects and cycles on a timeline, with issues grouped by project and status. We used it to plan a 3-month product launch across 6 cycles, and the visual timeline made dependencies and sequencing obvious in a way that Jira's roadmap never did. Stakeholders could see the plan without logging into the issue tracker — Linear generates shareable read-only roadmap links.</p>

      <p>The limitation is that Linear is agile-first. There are no Gantt charts, no waterfall planning, no dependency mapping beyond simple blocking relationships. If your team runs traditional waterfall or needs complex dependency graphs, Linear is not the right tool. For agile software teams, the built-in cycles and roadmap are a strength, not a weakness.</p>

      <h3>Offline Support and Mobile</h3>
      <p>Linear's local-first architecture means it works offline. We tested this on a 6-hour flight with no Wi-Fi — we triaged 40 issues, created 12 new ones, moved 8 between cycles, and added comments to 15. Everything synced within 30 seconds of reconnecting, with no conflicts or data loss. The offline experience is indistinguishable from the online experience for read and write operations.</p>

      <p>The mobile apps (iOS and Android) are also excellent. They cache the workspace locally, so you can triage issues on a phone with the same speed as the desktop. The mobile UI is a simplified version of the desktop UI — you lose some power features (bulk editing, advanced filters) but gain a focused triage experience. We used the mobile app to clear the backlog during commutes and found it genuinely productive, not just a fallback.</p>

      <p>The desktop apps (Mac and Windows) are native, not Electron wrappers. They feel fast, use native window chrome, and integrate with the OS notification system. We kept the Mac app open in the menu bar for quick issue creation via a global shortcut (Cmd+Shift+L). This is the kind of polish that distinguishes Linear from Jira, whose desktop app is a Chromium wrapper around the web UI.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>We tested Linear against three competing issue trackers. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Tool</th>
            <th>Price (per seat/mo)</th>
            <th>Speed</th>
            <th>Free for Teams</th>
            <th>Gantt Charts</th>
            <th>GitHub Sync</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Linear</strong></td>
            <td>$8</td>
            <td>Under 100ms</td>
            <td>No (solo only)</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Native</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Jira (Standard)</td>
            <td>$8</td>
            <td>1 to 3s</td>
            <td>Up to 10 users</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Plugin</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Asana (Starter)</td>
            <td>$11</td>
            <td>500ms to 2s</td>
            <td>Up to 10 users</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>Plugin</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>GitHub Projects</td>
            <td>Free</td>
            <td>300ms to 1s</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Native</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p><strong>Jira</strong> remains the default for enterprises, and the Standard plan at $8 per seat matches Linear on price. Jira's strengths are Gantt charts, custom fields, deep automation, and a mature integration ecosystem. Its weakness is speed — even with Jira's 2026 improvements, it is 10 to 30 times slower than Linear. For a head-to-head breakdown, see our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison.</p>

      <p><strong>Asana</strong> is the cross-functional alternative — marketing, ops, and design teams use it because it handles non-engineering workflows better than Linear. It costs $3 more per seat and is slower, but it has Gantt charts and a more flexible project model. If your team is not purely engineering, Asana is the better fit. See our <a href="/reviews/monday-vs-asana/">Monday vs Asana</a> comparison for details.</p>

      <p><strong>GitHub Projects</strong> is free and lives inside GitHub, so PR and issue linking is automatic. For small teams already on GitHub, it is a tempting zero-cost option. The trade-off is that it is not a full issue tracker — no cycles, no roadmap, no keyboard-first UI. If your team grows past 5 people or needs agile planning, you will outgrow GitHub Projects and end up on Linear or Jira anyway.</p>

      <p>For a deeper comparison of where each tool wins, see our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> breakdown — we ran both tools side by side for 30 days and tracked the differences.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Try Linear free for a solo workspace before you commit. The free tier is permanent for one user, so you can evaluate the speed, keyboard shortcuts, and GitHub integration without a credit card. If your team of 2 to 50 people ships software and values speed, the Standard plan at $8 per seat is a clear buy. <a href="https://linear.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow">Sign up on linear.app</a> to start the free tier.</p>

      <p>Choose the annual plan if your team is committed. Annual billing drops the Standard plan from $10 to $8 per seat per month — a 20% saving that adds up fast on a 10-person team ($240 per year). Monthly billing is the right pick if you are evaluating or expect churn.</p>

      <p>Skip Linear and stay on Jira if you need Gantt charts, custom fields, or deep enterprise automation. Linear is agile-first and explicitly does not support waterfall planning or complex dependency graphs. For enterprises with Sarbanes-Oxley compliance, scripted Jira automations, or 100+ person teams, Jira remains the safer choice. See our <a href="/reviews/linear-vs-jira/">Linear vs Jira</a> comparison.</p>

      <p>Consider Asana instead if your team is cross-functional. Linear is built for engineering — it has no marketing calendar, no design review workflow, no ops task templates. If marketing, design, and ops all share the issue tracker, Asana handles the non-engineering workflows better for $3 more per seat.</p>

      <p>Migrate from Jira using Linear's built-in importer. Linear imports Jira issues, projects, and labels in about an hour for a 5,000-issue workspace. The importer maps Jira statuses to Linear statuses, preserves comments and attachments, and maintains issue links. We migrated 3,200 issues with no data loss. Plan the migration for a Friday afternoon so the team starts fresh on Monday.</p>

      <p>Avoid Linear if you need built-in time tracking or expense management. Linear has no native time tracking — you will need a separate tool like Toggl, Harvest, or Clockify, connected via the API. For teams that bill clients by the hour, Jira with the Tempo plugin is a more complete solution. See our <a href="/reviews/notion-vs-obsidian/">Notion vs Obsidian</a> review for note-taking tools that pair with Linear.</p>

      <p>Pair Linear with <a href="/reviews/best-ai-coding-assistant-2026/">an AI coding assistant</a> and a <a href="/reviews/slack-vs-teams/">Slack or Teams</a> integration for a modern software workflow. Linear's Slack integration posts issue updates and cycle reminders to channels automatically.</p>

